about your moody poetry!

62
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:08,099
[MERCURIUS] I suppose
the question you want answered

63
00:05:08,183 --> 00:05:11,561
is why you are still alive.

64
00:05:11,645 --> 00:05:14,898
But that's a foolish
question for you to ask.

65
00:05:14,981 --> 00:05:17,901
You should already be
well aware of the answer.

66
00:05:17,984 --> 00:05:20,695
As long as you feel
that sense of déjà vu,

67
00:05:20,779 --> 00:05:22,781
death will never
be able to claim you.

68
00:05:22,864 --> 00:05:25,534
And as impossible as
it sounds, it's true.

69
00:05:25,617 --> 00:05:27,536
You cannot die.

70
00:05:27,619 --> 00:05:30,413
Because I won't let you perish
before your work is done.

71
00:05:30,497 --> 00:05:32,290
[SHIROU]
You what?

72
00:05:32,374 --> 00:05:33,667
[MERCURIUS]
I suppose I should start from

73
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:35,919
the beginning.

74
00:05:36,002 --> 00:05:37,712
When you were a young boy,

75
00:05:37,796 --> 00:05:39,923
a seemingly minor change
occurred in your life that would

76
00:05:40,006 --> 00:05:41,925
set your course.

77
00:05:42,008 --> 00:05:45,428
It began with the arrival of
your new neighbor, Ren Fujii.

78
00:05:45,512 --> 00:05:48,223
What did you think of him
that first time?

79
00:05:48,306 --> 00:05:49,474
[SHIROU]
Nothing.

80
00:05:49,558 --> 00:05:51,935
He just seemed kinda gloomy.

81
00:05:52,018 --> 00:05:54,312
[MERCURIUS]
Indeed, but was that all you

82
00:05:54,396 --> 00:05:56,690
thought about him, nothing more?

83
00:05:56,773 --> 00:05:58,608
If so, then why
did you build a

84
00:05:58,692 --> 00:06:00,735
friendship with him
in the first place?

85
00:06:00,819 --> 00:06:03,655
One that has lasted
to this very day.

86
00:06:04,531 --> 00:06:07,492
[REN whimpering]

87
00:06:21,798 --> 00:06:24,759
[chuckling]

88
00:06:34,853 --> 00:06:36,354
[KASUMI'S FATHER gags]

89
00:06:39,816 --> 00:06:41,526
[MERCURIUS]
You remember.

90
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:44,195
That sensation you
first felt that day,

91
00:06:44,279 --> 00:06:46,364
at that precise moment.

92
00:06:46,448 --> 00:06:49,242
That twinge at the
back of your mind.

93
00:06:49,326 --> 00:06:51,828
[SHIROU]
It felt like I'd done it before.

94
00:06:51,912 --> 00:06:53,622
[MERCURIUS]
Yes.

95
00:06:53,705 --> 00:06:57,167
That was the moment when
your déjà vu first began.

96
00:07:06,092 --> 00:07:07,969
[MERCURIUS]
The father in this sordid tale

97
00:07:08,053 --> 00:07:11,473
didn't have what most might
call an average background.

98
00:07:11,556 --> 00:07:14,267
His role was to cultivate a
subject of vital importance

99
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:15,936
in a project I'd
first envisioned

100
00:07:16,019 --> 00:07:18,396
during the height of
the Second World War.

101
00:07:20,190 --> 00:07:21,900
